Nice looking puzzle / adventure in the vein of Myst, with nice non-annoying soundtrack. However, the puzzle design leaves a lot to be desired after: lots of puzzles come without clues (perhaps except the ones you can purchase ...hey, hang on a second!), requiring to brute force them. There is also no story that I can discern after making it through about 1/3 of the game, which doesn't help with the immersion. And by the way, there is a peculiarly positioned bug: the portal between the 3rd and 5th screens is one way; the only way to get back to screen 5 is by purchasing the Fast Travel IAP. Not cool.

Ran into a game-breaking bug about halfway through. If you leave the screen with the smoky chimney, the coat disappears. Clicking on the chimney still says that it's filled with smoke but it won't let you use the glass jar on it. Not really interested in starting over from the beginning but at least it was free.  Up until that point the game was pretty good. It does a good job of having a lot of space available at any given time so it's not just one item -> one puzzle--you'll have several available puzzles at any given time and be searching for solutions.   Negatives are that there are a few items that I missed just because they were really small and not obvious at all on my phone. Also, as you get farther, a lot of the puzzles lose their logic and just become using every item you have on everything you run across until something works.   So 3 stars, closer to 3.5 but I'm salty about not being able to finish so I rounded down.

I was given to understand at the start of the game that there was a fourth book that you would explore when you find it. This is not the case, upon finding the fourth book the game ends with a promise that you can explore it in a future game. I found this a big disappointment and very misleading. With 3 books it was not the longest game in the world, how they will manage to get a game out of just one book is beyond me. Some of the puzzles would have been more enjoyable if there was a brief description of how to play them. There was also far too much skipping back and forth, most of the time I was unable to keep track of where I was or were I was supposed to go. This would have been made less annoying had the map allowed quick travel to the different locations.
